// JavaScript primitive subclasses — JS-coercive operator overlays
// on top of Sutra's own primitive classes.
//
// Per Emma 2026-05-10: "JavaScript primitives, they'd be sub-
// subclasses of our own classes but they function a bit
// differently and they have JavaScript operators on them."
//
// Inheritance shape:
//
//       Sutra primitives           JavaScriptObject (catch-all)
//          /     |       \                  |
//        int   String   bool   ...     (existing class)
//        /       |        \
//   JavaScriptInt  JavaScriptString  JavaScriptBool
//
// The subclasses are PRIMARILY structural — they let the operator
// dispatch's inheritance walk find the right overload. Most
// JS-specific behaviors (strict equality, truthy table, typeof,
// coercive +) live as canonical implementations on
// `JavaScriptObject`; subclasses route through those because the
// dispatch falls through to `JavaScriptObject` for any
// JavaScript-flavored value's coercion semantics.
//
// Each subclass also inherits its parent Sutra primitive's
// operators (e.g. `String`'s `+` for concat — see
// stdlib/strings.su). So `JavaScriptString + JavaScriptString` →
// `string_concat` via the inherited operator, with no separate
// declaration here.
//
// Design doc + open questions:
// planning/open-questions/javascript-primitive-subclasses.md.

class JavaScriptString extends String { }
class JavaScriptInt extends int { }
class JavaScriptFloat extends float { }
class JavaScriptBool extends bool { }
